==Abstract==

This IIP proposes increasing the maximum OP_RETURN output size from 83 bytes to 4,096 bytes to accommodate post-quantum cryptographic protocols.

==Motivation==

Post-quantum cryptographic primitives have larger data sizes:

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Algorithm !! Data Size
|-
| Kyber1024 public key || 1,568 bytes
|-
| Kyber1024 ciphertext || 1,568 bytes
|-
| Dilithium5 signature || 4,627 bytes
|-
| Dilithium5 public key || 2,592 bytes
|}

Protocols requiring OP_RETURN:
* IIP-47 Payment Codes (notification transactions)
* Future stealth addresses
* Timestamping services
* Cross-chain atomic swaps

==Specification==

===New Limit===

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Parameter !! Old Value !! New Value
|-
| MAX_OP_RETURN_SIZE || 83 bytes || 4,096 bytes
|}

===Activation===

Via version bits mechanism (IIP-37):

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Parameter !! Value
|-
| Deployment Name || extended_opreturn
|-
| Bit || 4
|-
| Start Time || Genesis
|-
| Timeout || None (NO_TIMEOUT)
|-
| Min Activation Height || 1,000 blocks
|-
| Threshold || 90%
|}

===Consensus Rules===

When DEPLOYMENT_EXTENDED_OPRETURN is '''ACTIVE''':
* OP_RETURN outputs up to 4,096 bytes valid
* Only one OP_RETURN output per transaction
* OP_RETURN outputs must have zero value

===Policy Changes===

<pre>
size_t maxOpReturn = IsDeploymentActive(DEPLOYMENT_EXTENDED_OPRETURN)
    ? MAX_OP_RETURN_SIZE_EXTENDED  // 4096
    : MAX_OP_RETURN_SIZE;          // 83
</pre>

==Rationale==

===Why 4 KB?===

* Sufficient for IIP-47 (~1.6 KB)
* Room for metadata and future extensions
* Not excessive (prevents abuse)
* Clean power-of-2 boundary

===Why Soft Fork?===

* Old nodes reject large OP_RETURN as non-standard
* Old nodes still validate blocks containing them
* No consensus-critical changes

==Security Considerations==

* 4 KB limit prevents large data dumps
* Fee economics discourage spam
* Block limits apply
* Single OP_RETURN per transaction maintained

